data.title: Awards & Recognition
data.meta_description: Follow the Purina® Pro Plan® Champions Cup standings and review the winners of the past Circle of Champions and the Purina Awards.
data.text:
National Championship, other major championship wins highlight phenomenal year

March Wright and her Labrador Retriever, Freeridin Rikki Tikki Tavi, tell their story of winning the 2023 National Retriever Championship

Meet Chris Flessner, the co-breeder/owner of the 2022 Westminster Best in Show winner, Trumpet. Hear the story behind their history-making win, and why Trumpet requires the fine-tuned nutrition Purina Pro Plan Sport.

What a grand win for “Winston,” a 3-year-old fawn French Bulldog who became the first of his breed to be awarded Best in Show at the 21st annual “National Dog Show Presented

Qualified for the 2021 National Open Retriever Championship, Mickey was No. 2 in the Purina High Point Open Retriever standings – an outcome that would play out at the National Open.

A show-off with natural bird sense and spot-on ability, a 4 ½-year-old ticked liver-and-white male English Cocker named “Ike” delivered a perfect balance of independence and teamwork to win the National Open Cocker Championship.

Consistent, quality bird hunting, determination and endurance in multiple National Shoot to Retrieve Association (NSTRA) field trials gave a 4 ½-year-old orange-and-white female English Setter named “Jill” the most points ever recorded.

Natural ability, quick brainwork and a lot of desire pushed a 7 ½-year-old red tick male Beagle to the front to win the National Hunting Beagle Association (NBHA) Sectional Series.

A gorgeous 4 ½-year-old brown brindle female Plott Hound named “Legs” continued her streak of consistency in a truly outstanding year of coonhound bench shows to win the 2021 UKC World Championship in September in Peru, Indiana.

Winning the 2021 Meeker Classic was the crown jewel for “Alice,” a 9 ½-year-old rough black-ticked tricolor Border Collie. One of the toughest sheepdog competitions in North America, arguably the world, drew a large entry of 170 teams.

Natural-born bird sense, keen desire and youthful athleticism came together for a 1 ½-year-old white-and-liver Pointer named “Ivy” who won the New England Open Grouse Championship in her derby career.
